Social Resilience Notebook

This is an R Markdown Notebook for preliminary Social Resilience analyses.

We begin by examining basic statistics for parcels in Davidson County.

#setwd('C:/Users/nelsonks/Box Sync/Kate_Kevona/NashvilleFloodData')
#setwd('E:/kate/Box Sync/Kate_Kevona/NashvilleFloodData')
wd<- getwd()

years<-seq(2002,2016)
n<-length(years)

for (i in 1:n){

  assign( paste0("p",years[i],"_dat"), readRDS(paste0(wd,"/data/","parceldata",years[i],".RDS")))
  name<-get(paste0("p",years[i],"_dat"))

  # hist(name$SALE_PRICE[name$SALE_PRICE<=2000000],

}

Now we add a year identifier to each set of parcel data and then combine all years of data into a single long-format dataset. The trends through time for parcels are then plotted using running averages.

Now we upload the parcel shapefile and build a spatial object using the most recent parcel shapefile (2016) available. Due to computational intensity of building an adjacency matrix for a ~300,000 by ~300,000 matrix create a continuous SPDE mesh based on the centroids of the parcel polygons instead.

library(sp)
library(INLA)

We would now like to see how the spatial effect is distributed across Davidson County. We do this by projecting the estimated effects onto a spatial grid.

bounds<-extent(shp) #find the min and max extents of Davidson County for grid creation

stepsize<-1/111 #should give a roughly 1km by 1km pixel grid-->check this, something is off

nxy<-round(c(diff(range(bounds@xmax, bounds@xmin)), diff(range(bounds@ymin,bounds@ymax)))/stepsize) #number of pixels

projgrid<-inla.mesh.projector(mesh, xlim=range(bounds@xmax, bounds@xmin),ylim=range(bounds@ymin,bounds@ymax),dims=nxy) #associate inla mesh with grid

xmean<-inla.mesh.project(projgrid, null$summary.random$s$mean) #associate the estimates with the grid
xsd<-inla.mesh.project(projgrid, null$summary.random$s$sd)

#combine the results with the locations in a dataframe
 test<-as.vector(xmean)
      test2<-as.vector(xsd)
      t<-cbind(projgrid$lattice$loc, test,test2)
      t<- as.data.frame(t)
      colnames(t)<-c("x","y","mean","sd")

#remove parts of the plot outside the county border
library(lattice)
library(sp)
library(rgeos)
library(maptools)
## Checking rgeos availability: TRUE
      coordinates(t)<-cbind(t$x,t$y)
      proj4string(t)<-proj4string(shp)
      tclip<-t[shp,]
      plot(tclip)

      gridded(tclip)<-TRUE
      plot(tclip)

#plot the spatial effect estimates      
      plot(tclip[ ,"mean"], main="Mean Spatial Effect on Tax Change")
